href=\"http://www.illustratedwildlife.com/\">Chris Shields</a></small></div>\r\nMammal\r\n<p class=\"wildlife-latin\">Pipistrellus pipistrellus</p>\r\nPipistrelles are tiny bats with reddish-brown coats and blackish-brown ears, nose and wing membranes. They are common throughout Britain. Like other bats, pipistrelles are nocturnal. They emerge at dusk to feed for a couple of hours before returning to their roosts.\r\n\r\nIn the winter they hibernate in trees and buildings. In the summer they use trees, buildings and bat boxes to roost. Pipistrelles are agile, fast fliers.\r\n\r\nDuring the breeding season males defend a territory, Females visit these territories and after mating give birth in June and July, usually to a single baby. Bats are mammals and feed their young milk. After about three or four weeks the young bats are able to fly and leave the roosts in August.\r\n\r\n<strong>IMPORTANT</strong>: if you find a sick or ailing bat, youÂ should not approach or handle the animal but seek advice from the Bat Conservation Trust.\r\n<h3>What does it eat?</h3>\r\nSmall insects, such as moths and gnats. A single pipistrelle can eat 3,000 gnats in one night.\r\n<h3>When will I see it?</h3>\r\nAt dusk and during the night from April until September.\r\n<h3>Where will I see it?</h3>\r\nFlying throughout the garden at night. Also in parks, open woodland, marshes, farmland and urban areas.','Kingsland Basin Bat Survey','','publish','open','open','','kingsland-basin-bat-survey','','','2013-05-27 22:37:00','2013-05-27 21:37:00','',0,'http://chug.org.uk/?p=209',0,'post','',0),(210,1,'2013-05-26 21:44:03','2013-05-26 20:44:03','In 2012 CHUG commissioned a bat survey of the Basin to discover more about their local bat population.','ASW_batsurvey_173-1','Kingsland Basin Bat Survey','inherit','open','open','','asw_batsurvey_173-1','','','2013-05-26 21:44:03','2013-05-26 20:44:03','',209,'http://chug.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/ASW_batsurvey_173-1.doc',0,'attachment','applic